<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / Ex-wife's right to money upheld
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Court of Appeal yesterday paved the way to dividing personal pension
rights on divorce when it rejected an appeal brought by a husband, Mr
Brooks, to prevent some of his pension being transferred to his former wife.
Mr Norman Russell of Paisner &amp; Co, solicitors acting for the ex-wife, said
that the decision went further than a High Court judgment in April 1993
which upheld a district judge's order to vary Mr Brooks' pension fund as a
result of his divorce after 12 years of marriage.
The High Court judgment maintained that Mr Brooks' pension fund fell within
the definition of a 'post-nuptial settlement'. Divorce law gives courts the
power to vary the terms of a post-nuptial settlement, therefore allowing Mr
Brooks' pension to be varied in his ex-wife's favour.
The High Court decision was widely regarded as applicable only in
circumstances similar to those of the case, which involved a
self-administered pension scheme with a surplus.
Yesterday's decision appeared to have much wider application, although the
Court of Appeal's ruling that a pension could not be varied if a third party
is involved eliminates application of the judgment to company schemes.
The appeal was rejected in a 2-1 decision in which Lord Justices Neill and
Waite rejected the appeal while Lord Justice Hoffmann upheld it. Lord Waite
said that, because private pensions 'are too numerous and too varied to be
treated empirically as a class', courts should examine arrangements to
decide whether the act of a spouse joining a scheme involved creation of a
post-nuptial settlement and whether the scheme should be varied by the
court.
No one at Girling, Mr Brooks' solicitors, was available for comment but an
appeal to the House of Lords is thought likely.
Mr Robin Ellison of Hammond Suddards, pension solicitors, and a member of
the pensions and divorce working group of the Pensions Management Institute,
said: 'If it is upheld in the House of Lords it will make personal pensions
a less attractive bet for husbands than company schemes.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
