<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / Major puts animals on agenda
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Tories yesterday attempted to soften their 'hunting-and-shooting' image
 -making animal welfare a central policy in their European campaign
alongside farming, fishing and the countryside.
They launched a dossier, Animal Welfare - The Conservative Record, listing
government action on animal experiments, whaling, elephants, wildlife,
dangerous and stray dogs and farm animals.
In the foreword, Mr John Major, the prime minister, writes: 'The welfare of
animals is no longer a fringe issue.
'Most people feel that there is room to improve the way animals are treated.
No other government - in Britain or abroad - can match the record of this
Conservative government on animal welfare.
'We have taken comprehensive steps to strengthen the protection of animals
in the wild, on the farm and in laboratories.'
At a news conference at Conservative Central Office, Mr Nicholas Soames,
junior agriculture minister, said: 'Historically, we in the British Isles
have taken pride on our efforts to protect animals from cruelty and
neglect.'
Mrs Gillian Shephard, agriculture minister, attacked Labour for seeing the
countryside as 'an urban playground', and the Liberal Democrats for failing
to mention animal welfare in their manifesto.
