<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / MP urges probe of utility regulators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Richard Caborn, chairman of the Commons trade and industry committee, has
called for a royal commission to examine the performance of utility
regulators and the effectiveness of different regulatory regimes.
Mr Caborn, a Labour MP, said regulation had become 'a substitute for
policymaking, with crucial decisions left in the hands of unelected and
unaccountable regulators'.
He said areas which needed to be covered included the accountability of
regulators; the feasibility of streamlining the various agencies,
particularly in the energy sector; the role of the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission and the Office of Fair Trading; and the case for widening the
regulatory role to include the right to review spending on research and
development.
Fierce competition will remain in world coal markets until well into the
next century, Mr Neil Clarke, British Coal chairman, said yesterday.
However by the mid to late 1990s, prices agreed in contracts with generators
will be truly competitive with contract prices of imported coal delivered to
inland power stations.
</TEXT>
