<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / US sued in airbase pollution claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Anglian Water is suing the US government for allegedly polluting its water
supply in a legal action which tests the findings of a recent landmark case
in the UK on pollution liability, Peggy Hollinger writes.
Friends of the Earth, the environment campaign group, revealed yesterday
that Anglian is alleging in the High Court that a water supply was polluted
by a US military petrol station at RAF Mildenhall in Suffolk. Anglian is
suing the US government for more than Pounds 500,000, which it claims is the
cost of treating the water and installing protective systems to prevent
further pollution.
The action comes just six months after Cambridge Water lost a similar suit
against Eastern Counties Leather, the tanning company, although it was ruled
that some polluters could be liable if they could reasonably have foreseen
the effects of their actions.
Anglian's writ alleges that the US military authorities were negligent in
allowing petrol to escape into the soil and for failing to check for leaks.
Friends of the Earth said yesterday that several other military bases were
polluters.
</TEXT>
