<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / British Gas hits at constraints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Gas yesterday called for the early lifting of regulations that
restrict its activities in the commercial market of consumers who use more
than 2,500 therms a year.
Mr Cedric Brown, chief executive, told an energy conference in London that
government efforts designed to promote competition were now
'anti-competitive, because they tilt the playing field in favour of other
companies'.
British Gas has to reduce its share of the market for users of more than
2,500 therms to 55 per cent by 1995. However Mr Brown said market share
constraints had already resulted in competitors capturing 45 per cent of the
market.
Mr Brown also complained that British Gas was subsidising independent gas
marketers that used the gas pipeline system. 'It makes a nonsense of free
market forces . . . and is sending false signals to end users of gas.'
He rejected competitors' allegations that British Gas had overvalued its
transportation system.
Ofgas, the industry regulator, will announce early next month the formula
which will govern the prices that British Gas will be able to charge for
transportation, and the rate of return it can earn on its transportation
assets.
Mr Brown warned that the phased opening of the domestic market, due to begin
in 1996, was a 'massive experiment' affecting 18m households, and that there
was 'precious little time to work out potential problems'.
Mr Jonathan Stern, a fellow at the Royal Institute of International Affairs,
also warned about possible problems of adhering to the government's
ambitious timetable. He suggested that it might be best if legislation to
open up the domestic sector slipped by a year to give the industry more time
to work out potential problems.
Ms Clare Spottiswoode, Ofgas director-general, conceded that de-regulation
on such a scale had not been attempted elsewhere. She said Ofgas was aware
that a number of problems needed to be solved before competition was
introduced'.
Ms Spottiswoode, who has been caught up in a political controversy over her
refusal to pass on to consumers the costs of energy savings schemes, said
Ofgas will publish a paper on the subject in July.
She hoped it would spark off 'an extensive debate in parliament'.
Ms Spottiswoode said British Gas and Ofgas were looking at ways in which
they could promote energy efficiency without having to tax consumers.
</TEXT>
