<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / Accountant fails in appeal over censure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A leading accountant yesterday lost his appeal against a finding that he
failed adequately to supervise an employee who was convicted of forgery and
deception.
Mr Brian Worth, a former head of the investigation committee of the
Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales, was 'admonished' by
its disciplinary committee last November. The action was over his
supervisory action while chairman of Clark Kenneth Levanthal, an
international network of accountancy firms including Clark Whitehill in the
UK.
The institute investigation was triggered in late 1991 after the conviction
of Mr Nicholas Young, a former executive director of CKL. Mr Worth resigned
from the investigation committee later in 1991.
The appeal committee yesterday said it found the complaint proved and
ordered Mr Worth to pay Pounds 1,000 costs.
Mr Young used CKL's address and stationery to attract investors and claimed
their money would be invested in offshore trusts. In fact it was used to bet
on horse races.
Clark Whitehill said: 'We are entirely clear that we have no legal
liability.' Mr Worth's solicitors said the institute had found he had no
connection with or knowledge of the fraud, and he had received the mildest
punishment possible.
</TEXT>
