<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / Shakespeare festival at Barbican
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The first large-scale international Shakespeare festival in the UK is to be
held at the Barbican Centre, London, from October 25 to November 20.
The festival is being planned by the Royal Shakespeare Company, which is
resident at the Barbican. It would be the most ambitious event there and
draw on all the arts complex's resources.
Among directors taking part will be the American Peter Sellars, with an
updated version of The Merchant of Venice; Karin Beler from Germany with a
controversial Romeo and Juliet; and the Japanese director Tadashi Suzuki,
with King Lear. There will also be companies from Georgia and Israel.
Music will include the Gothenburg Symphony Orchestra giving the concert
premiere of Sibelius' music for The Tempest, with highlights from the play.
The Barbican cinemas and exhibition spaces will also be given over to
Shakespeare. The Pounds 1.25m festival is supported by a Pounds 500,000
grant from the City of London.
</TEXT>
