<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Gatt 'would welcome renewal'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Peter Sutherland, director-general of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade, would welcome a decision by President Clinton to renew China's
trade privileges.
This would have an indirect bearing on China's bid for re-entry to the world
trade system. 'Gatt has no responsibility in the area of political issues
which underly the issue of Most Favoured Nation status, but the MFN decision
has an indirect effect on the negotiations because MFN policy is relevant to
Gatt members,' he said.
China has stated its desire to be a founder member of the World Trade
Organisation which - subject to international ratification - comes into
being on January 1. The country was a Gatt founder member but quit after the
communists came to power in 1949.
Mr Sutherland recently returned from Beijing, where he found a great
willingness to re-enter Gatt and meet its entry requirements. The prospects
for resolving outstanding issues must be assisted by a satisfactory
conclusion to any issues outstanding with one of the world's biggest
traders, he said.
To secure membership, China had to improve the transparency of its existing
trade regime, demonstrate uniformity in applying those laws, clarify how its
trading companies operate, and elucidate tariff and non-tariff barriers. But
Mr Sutherland stressed that significant steps had already been taken in both
trade and foreign exchange regimes.
While questioning China's ability to become a member by January 1, Mr
Sutherland has every confidence in the WTO itself being in place by then.
'I believe Mr Clinton is absolutely committed to the January 1 date, and I
believe it's very important that the US as a leading trading country with an
absolute interest in the development of the multilateral system should
provide leadership in this area, and it seems it is determined to do so.'
</TEXT>
