<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / HK property men give land price warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hong Kong property developers yesterday got together to secure prices at a
land auction that were sharply lower than market expectations, in
retaliation against government efforts to bring down soaring prices for
housing.
One analyst described the government auction, which saw bidders rushing
around the hall to round up those proposing higher bids, as 'the most
blatant display of property developers' cartel in anyone's recent memory'.
The inability of many families to afford their own homes prompted Mr Chris
Patten, Hong Kong's governor, to launch a task force in March, which has
been instructed to come up with means of cooling prices.
The government took a small step in this direction last month by slightly
increasing the supply of residential land it will sell off this year.
It is understood a consortium of up to 12 bought the biggest plot, with 10
teaming up for the smaller one. Those joining forces included some of the
colony's biggest developers.
The first site, of 20,780 square metres in the New Territories' Fanling
area, went for HKDollars 2.04bn (Pounds 171m) against market expectations of
HKDollars 3bn to HKDollars 4bn, while the smaller Yuen Long plot, of about
5,889 square metres, went under the hammer for HKDollars 510m. It was
expected to reach as much as HKDollars 800m.
These prices do not appear to signal the start of a big slide in prices.
Three external factors stood to depress the final prices secured: the
government's pledge, which has already pruned asking prices on finished
flats, a clutch of other quality sites coming on line at the same time, and
further sites in the pipeline.
Both the plots sold off yesterday are slightly inconvenient for transport,
and both towns are an hour's commuting from the central business district.
According to Mr Michael Green, director of SG Warburg in Hong Kong, the
Fanling site splits into 12 plots, so each developer will be able to assume
his own portion while spreading any risk.
But he added: 'It is a reality that the developers formed a consortium. It
clearly is a message to the government not to interfere with the free market
mechanism.'
Property prices have been on an upward track since 1990; the price of small
flats has risen by some 200 per cent in the past three years. New apartments
yielding little more space than the average suburban two-up-two-down were
sold last month for between HKDollars 10m and HKDollars 15m.
</TEXT>
