<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / PC screen text fails the test of readability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you find it hard to read words on a personal computer screen, you are in
good company.
A leading US-based computer scientist warned last night that even the best
of today's personal computer screens could not display extended text, such
as newspaper articles or encyclopaedia entries, so they can be read in
comfort.
The better a reader you are, he said, the more difficulty you will
experience in reading from a screen.
Mr Alan Kay, widely credited as the inspiration behind many of the
best-known features of personal computers, including screen 'windows' and
the 'mouse' pointing device, said the discovery called into question the use
of computers in schools for teaching reading.
He said: 'It is almost a crime to put computers into schools to teach
reading because nothing is more antagonistic to the act of reading than a
conventional computer screen.'
It also raises questions about the suitability of personal computer
technology for on-line text retrieval and other information and
entertainment services.
Mr Kay, formerly a top scientist for Xerox and now research fellow at Apple
Computer, was giving the sixth Charles Read Memorial lecture in London. He
is now studying the use of computers in educating children.
Mr Kay's conclusions were based on experiments carried out using equipment
built for the US space programme and capable of detecting minute eye
movements. They show that, close to a screen, the eye is capable of
detecting minute changes in light intensity as the image is refreshed, and
these are unconsciously recorded by the viewer.
The brain interprets them as warning signals in a throwback to the days when
humans had to be alert to the possibility of sudden charges by sabre-toothed
tigers and the like. The eyes, in consequence, wander continually to the
edges of the screen to try to identify the danger.
Mr Kay said it was technically possible to build a screen suitable for
reading text. It would have 6.3m picture elements (pixels) compared with the
300,000 on a typical PC screen.
It would have a contrast ratio similar to white paper of 100:1 compared to
30:1 for a computer screen; and it would refresh the screen at more than 100
frames a second.
Such a screen, built at Xerox's research headquarters, had cost Dollars
200,000 (Pounds 133,333). Screens of equivalent quality might be available
at an economic price in five years, he thought.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3571 Electronic Computers.
    P8733 Noncommercial Research Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
    TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
