<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / Clinton to renew China's favoured trade status: US drops
insistence on link to Beijing's human rights record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton, promising a 'larger and more productive '
relationship with China, last night dropped his insistence that US trade
preferences should be linked to improvements in China's human rights record.
'I believe we are far more likely to have human rights advances when it is
not under the cloud of the annual renewal of MFN,' the president said,
referring to the most favoured nation trading status, which allows Chinese
goods into the US at low tariffs.
Mr Clinton offered some consolation to those in Congress and elsewhere who
have demanded sustained pressure on Chinese human rights. He announced a ban
on imports of Chinese guns and ammunition, mainly the SKS rifle popular in
the US, as well as committing himself to 'aggressive' efforts on the human
rights front.
But he freely conceded that his executive order of last summer linking trade
and human rights, setting a deadline of June 3 for MFN renewal, had not
produced the desired dividends, in spite of improvements in areas such as
emigration from China, prison labour and a better accounting of dissidents
in Tibet and throughout China.
The president thought that even his critics had come round to the view that
a different approach was necessary.
That may not stop some in Congress from introducing legislation either
maintaining the human rights linkage or demanding tougher sanctions than
implied by the guns and ammunition ban, which affects only an estimated
Dollars 15m-Dollars 20m (Pounds 10m-Pounds 13.3m) in Chinese sales out of
total Chinese exports last year of more than Dollars 31bn.
Mr Clinton placed his decision in the context of overall US policies in
Asia, as well as its 'significant interests' with China itself. He cited
this week's progress in trade negotiations with Japan and the 'possible
progress' in resolving the impasse over North Korea's nuclear ambitions.
His decision was one of the most difficult of his presidency. In the 1992
campaign he had accused President George Bush of 'coddling' the Chinese
dictatorship and had seemed to live up to that promise last summer with the
order linking MFN and human rights.
That action was commended at the time as politically astute, but it depended
on the co-operation of China. That was never seriously forthcoming.
Gatt chief welcomes MFN renewal, Page 7
Learning to trust others in China, Page 13
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CNZ  China, Asia.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
