<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets (America): US equities lifted by
Treasury bond auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Bonds set the direction for blue chip stocks yesterday, pulling them down in
the morning and helping to push them modestly higher during the afternoon,
writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 10.13 better at 3,755.30, after
recovering from a 24-point mid-morning deficit. The more broadly based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was up 1.52 at 456.33 in moderate NYSE volume of 254m
shares.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite edged 0.07 ahead to
439.25, and the Nasdaq composite inched up 0.61 to 732.08.
From the opening bell to close, the mood closely paralleled the vagaries of
the bond market. Early on, equity investors were forced to contend with an
unlikely combination of negatives - weak economic news alongside further
declines by Treasuries.
Though indications of an economic slowdown are often worrying to
shareholders betting on strong growth in corporate earnings, such data often
trigger an upturn in bonds because of the improved outlook on inflation,
which would eat into the value of fixed-rate investments. But higher bond
prices, and a concurrent decline in yields, are usually a plus for equities.
Yesterday morning, however, Treasury prices receded in spite of the Commerce
Department's announcement that orders of durable goods last month had grown
by a meagre 0.1 per cent, against expectations of a solid 1.0 per cent gain.
The bond market shrugged off the development amid concern over an afternoon
note auction.
The double blow hit stocks across the board. But when the Treasury auction
was completed successfully, longer-dated government bonds reversed course
and moved higher. Stocks followed suit, and the Dow industrials nudged into
positive ground in the final hour.
The session's most notable loser was Gtech Holdings, which plummeted Dollars
12 7/8 , or 37 per cent, to Dollars 22 3/4 . The company, which designs and
operates on-line lotteries and games, warned that net income in fiscal 1995
would not show improvement on fiscal 1994.
On the Nasdaq, Video Lottery Technologies plunged Dollars 3 to Dollars 14
1/4 after the UK government named its rival, Camelot Group, to operate a new
national lottery. Ironically, Gtech is a member of the Camelot consortium.
Among the Dow industrials, trading in Philip Morris was halted for the
entire session, while its board was meeting amid stepped-up pressure to
consider splitting the company's tobacco and food operations into separate
entities. After the close, the company revealed it would take no action on
the proposal. The stock fell 2.7 per cent to Dollars 53 3/4 the previous
session.
Technology issues again generated activity but the results were mixed.
Hewlett-Packard had dropped Dollars 2 1/8 soon after the computer maker
suggested during the analysts' briefing that its revenue growth may begin to
slow from the current rate of 20 per cent. But the stock regained its stride
to finish off Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 81 1/4 .
Elsewhere, Compaq Computer jumped Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars 119 1/4 on news
that it had displaced IBM and Apple as the world's leading supplier of
personal computers.
On the Nasdaq, Chiron dropped Dollars 42 3/64 to Dollars 62 17/64 after
Montgomery Securities downgraded the biotechnology company. Computer stocks
were mixed, with Lotus sheding Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 63 1/4 and Cyrix
adding Dollars 2 to Dollars 28.
Canada
Toronto stocks closed mixed in continued quiet trading. The TSE 300
composite index edged up 4.39, or 0.10 per cent, to 4291.37 in volume of
48.2m shares.
Stocks spent most of the day in negative territory before posting a small
gain in the last hour.
None of the 14 stock groups showed major swings. Banking and mining rose a
little, energy, industrial products and golds were flat, and consumer
products increased moderately.
Bank of Montreal rose CDollars  1/2 to CDollars 26 1/8 after reporting
slightly higher second-quarter earnings.
Hudson's Bay Co gained CDollars  1/8 to CDollars 31 5/8 on reporting its
first first-quarter profit since 1979.
Brazil
Sao Paulo closed up 8.1 per cent in heavy trade on bullish sentiment over
the presidential race. The Bovespa index rose 1,740 at 23,018 points in high
turnover of Cr406.4bn.
Analysts said the breaking of the 22,800 resistance level charted a new
bullish trend. They warned about profit-taking at tomorrow's opening.
Mexico
Equities closed virtually flat after a roller coaster session punctuated by
profit-taking and a technical rebound.
The key IPC index closed up 3.64 points at 2,472.16 - a gain of 0.15 per
cent. Volume totaled a moderate 1.6bn new pesos, on 139.2m shares traded.
</TEXT>
