<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / International Company News: Carter Holt ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Carter Holt Harvey, the forestry group which has interests in New Zealand
and Chile, yesterday reported a 34 per cent rise in tax-paid profits to
NZDollars 325m (USDollars 191.16m), reflecting cost-cutting and efficiency
measures over the past 12 months, writes Terry Hall in Wellington.
The chief executive, Mr David Oskin, said that during the coming year the
company intended to extend its operations into offshore markets in
Australia, Asia and South America and to take aim to become a leading force
within the Pacific Rim area.
Operating earnings before interest and tax rose 55 per cent to NZDollars
368m.
Turnover was NZDollars 2,476m, against NZDollars 2,461m a year ago, and tax
was NZDollars 90m, up from NZDollars 19m.
International Paper of New York manages Carter Holt Harvey and is the
biggest shareholder with 24 per cent.
In March, Brierley Investments effectively wound down the joint venture
which controlled the company by selling International Paper an 8 per cent
stake. BIL retains 7 per cent.
</TEXT>
