<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / International Company News: Comcast UK's IPO postponed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON and PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Plans by Comcast UK Cable Partners to raise funds through a secondary share
issue in the US were put on hold yesterday when underwriters postponed the
sale because of poor conditions in the market for initial public offerings
of stock.
The decision comes at a crucial time for cable companies in the UK which
have announced, or are considering, flotations in London.
Comcast UK Cable Partners, a unit of the Philadelphia-based cable
communications group Comcast, had initially planned to sell 11.75m shares
for up to Dollars 18 each.
The US IPO market, however, has been extremely weak in recent months, and
the underwriters, led by investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette,
struggled to find buyers.
Comcast is believed to have set a floor for the issue of around Dollars 14 a
share, and when investors showed little interest at that level, the offering
was postponed.
Analysts in New York were not overly concerned by the postponement. Ms
Jessica Reif, cable industry analyst at the US brokerage house Oppenheimer,
said: 'The economics of the business are still sound . . . It was just that
the IPO market stinks.'
In London analysts acknowledged that the Comcast decision might have an
impact on the timing of some flotations although they expect the debut of
TeleWest, the UK's largest cable operator, to go ahead next month as
planned.
Most said they did not expect it to affect the valuation of TeleWest which
is believed to have strong institutional support.
Last month TeleWest, a joint venture between TCI of Denver, the largest
cable operator, and US West, the American telephone company, confirmed its
plans to come to market through a global share offering expected to value
the group at around Pounds 1.7bn (Dollars 2.55bn).
TeleWest plans to seek a full listing for its shares on the London Stock
Exchange and a registration of American depository shares on Nasdaq.
Yesterday Mr Alan Michels, TeleWest chief executive, dismissed suggestions
that the postponed Comcast secondary issue would have any effect on its
plans, arguing that TeleWest was 'a special case'.
'We will still get a good reception in both the UK and US markets,' he said.
The company and its financial advisers will be meeting institutional
investors over the next few days and are expected to price the issue
shortly.
</TEXT>
