<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / International Company News: Hydro-Quebec up 23% at CDollars
643m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hydro-Quebec, one of Canada's two biggest electric power utilities earned
CDollars 643m (USDollars 465.9m) in the first quarter, up 23.7 per cent from
a year earlier, as harsh winter weather boosted domestic and export demand.
Electricity sales rose 8.4 per cent by volume and revenues 8.2 per cent to
CDollars 2.3bn. Sales in Quebec rose 3.8 per cent by volume and revenues by
6.4 per cent. A rate rise generated an additional CDollars 32m in the latest
period.
Revenues from power exports, mainly to the US, but also other provinces,
were up 4.4 per cent to CDollars 144m.
Spending rose 3.3 per cent largely because new generating and transmission
equipment came on stream, increasing depreciation and amortisation.
Tight controls held operating costs steady, while taxes were up 7.5 per
cent. The utility cut staff, controlled overtime strictly and began a pay
freeze.
Hydro-Quebec, 100 per cent owned by the Quebec government, invested CDollars
629m in the quarter, down from CDollars 755m a year earlier. Total
investment in 1994 will be CDollars 3.86bn, against CDollars 4bn last time,
mostly for James Bay hydro expansion and for the distribution system. Many
large projects are nearing completion.
The utility arranged a CDollars 1bn global issue and total 1994 borrowing
will be almost CDollars 3bn.
Cancellation of a US export contract to take effect in 1999 will not affect
the utility's construction programme. An existing 800 MW contract may be
extended beyond 1998 expiry.
</TEXT>
