<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / International Company News: Shares fall in troubled German
metal group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Metallgesellschaft dropped 15 per cent yesterday following the
disclosure on Tuesday night that the Frankfurt-based group will have to make
fresh provisions to cover newly-identified risks arising from its oil
operations in north America.
The group's shares fell DM40 to DM220 in after-market trading - a quarter
lower than the year's high of DM292 reached last week but still well above
the low point of DM175 to which they fell in the aftermath of its DM3.4bn
(Dollars 2bn) rescue package this January.
The metals, mining and industrial group refused yesterday to put a figure to
the new provisions. In its statement on Tuesday it said it planned to sell
its 80 per cent stake in the Buderus engineering company and other assets to
make the new provisions and cover the costs of further restructuring charges
in its German smelting activities.
Buderus made pre-tax profits of DM133m last year on sales of DM2.77bn. A
manufacturer of heating equipment and other products used primarily by the
building trade, it has a market capitalisation of DM1.6bn, valuing
Metallgesellschaft's 80 per cent stake at DM1.28bn. The sale of the stake is
likely to take place in the next few weeks.
'Metallgesellschaft's problems were meant to have been cleared up,' said one
analyst, who predicted that the provision could amount to DM1bn or more.
Metallgesellschaft said the new provisions arose as a result of contracts
made between MG Corp, a Metallgesellschaft subsidiary in New York, and
Castle Energy Corporation, an oil-refinery in which MG Corp owns a minority
stake.
This has no connection with MG Corp's oil futures trading which incurred
total losses of DM2.3bn in 1993-94, bringing Metallgesellschaft to the brink
of bankruptcy earlier this year.
</TEXT>
