<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / International Company News: Nokia to raise more than FM2bn
in global issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nokia, the Finnish telecommunications group, yesterday announced plans to
raise more than FM2bn (Dollars 370m) of new equity in the biggest
international share issue ever made by a Finnish company.
Up to 6m new preferred shares will be offered, increasing total outstanding
shares to 74.9m. At yesterday's closing price of FM410, the issue would
raise more than FM2.4bn.
The offer could take foreign ownership in the group above 50 per cent. An
estimated 46 per cent of the company's capital is already held by
foreigners, compared with 20 per cent a year ago. Around 90 per cent of the
shares will be targeted at non-Finnish institutions, with the balance being
offered on the domestic market.
Most of the international offer will be directed at the US, where the
company plans to seek a listing for its preferred stock, in the form of
American depositary receipts, on the New York Stock Exchange.
Mr Jorma Ollila, Nokia's president, said the funds would be used to finance
the group's rapidly-growing telecommunications and mobile phone businesses
and to strengthen its balance sheet. It will bring down gearing from 52 per
cent at the end of last year.
It is the group's second big share issue in a year, after it successfully
raised FM918m last summer. The buying has been driven by a sharp improvement
in Nokia's performance. Last year pre-tax profits were FM1.15bn after a
FM158m loss in 1992.
The company, the world's second biggest supplier of mobile phones after
Motorola of the US, has seen huge growth in sales of mobile phone and fixed
telephone equipment. Its share price has risen five-fold from FM82 at the
beginning of 1993.
Nokia intends to launch the issue during the summer, but is first seeking
shareholder approval at an extraordinary general meeting on June 23. Its
shares fell FM21, or nearly 5 per cent, on yesterday's announcement.
</TEXT>
