FT  26 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Chamberlin &amp; Hill shows 11% decline to
Pounds 1.42m
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Chamberlin &amp; Hill, the maker of iron castings, electrical conduit fittings
and switchgear, reported a near 11 per cent decline in pre-tax profits from
Pounds 1.59m to Pounds 1.42m for the year to end-March.
The outcome was struck on turnover up by 8 per cent, from Pounds 20.3m to
Pounds 22m. Interest payable was Pounds 131,000 (Pounds 141,000) and after
tax of Pounds 288,000 (Pounds 441,000) earnings per share came out at 15.78p
(16.07p).
Despite the fall in earnings directors are recommending an unchanged final
dividend of 4.5p, making 6.5p (6.25p) for the year.
Mr John Eccles, chairman, said the second half of the year had proved more
volatile than expected and the forecast improvement in the trading position
following high levels of capital expenditure at the Bloxwich foundry did not
materialise.
In addition, Fitter &amp; Poulton ended the year with second half profits well
below its estimates as a result of price competition and sharply reduced
margins.
