<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Lasmo hits out at Enterprise accounting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE and PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The battle for control of Lasmo shifted gear yesterday as the UK oil
explorer accused its rival and predator, Enterprise Oil, of flattering
profits with unacceptable accounting practices.
Mr Rudolf Agnew, Lasmo chairman, alleged in a letter to shareholders that
Enterprise Oil had breached UK accounting practices in its treatment of
acquisitions. He claimed earnings would benefit by Pounds 650m. He
questioned the value of Enterprise's Pounds 1.4bn all-paper bid in light of
the accounting practices.
Lasmo's document alleges that Enterprise's accounting methods are out of
step with the oil and gas industry and cast doubt on the viability of the
dividend. It states that Enterprise's practice of writing off substantial
sums on acquisitions results in a lower depreciation charge and thus higher
profits. The write-offs cannot be attributable to goodwill, since this does
not arise on oil and gas assets.
'Both UK and US accounting standards require asset purchases of this type to
be recorded at the prices paid,' the company said. Yet the adjustments were
revealed only in US documents reconciling UK to US earnings.
'They have attacked us for openly and publicly writing off Pounds 500m
whereas they have secretly written off Pounds 600m,' Mr Agnew said.
Enterprise counter-attacked by noting that Lasmo had been one of its
shareholders at the time of two deals. Mr Julian West, head of corporate
development, said they had discussed the accounting treatment and 'they were
happy to book the Enterprise profits'.
Mr West accused Lasmo of pursuing 'an Arabian nights defence of a succession
of tall stories'.
Enterprise also rejected Lasmo's charge that it was over-distributing
uncovered dividends. 'We have never borrowed to pay the dividend,
exploration or overheads,' he said.
Analysts said the attack on the profit and loss account had been
over-played. 'It is really the balance sheet and cash flow which are
important to exploration and production companies,' said Mr Howard
Cattermole, of Strauss Turnbull. None believed that Enterprise or
accountants KPMG Peat Marwick would deliberately breach accounting
standards.
Accounting issues, Page 29
</TEXT>
