<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Warburg names heirs to top jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SG Warburg, the UK-based investment bank, yesterday put to rest speculation
about the succession of the firm's top management, saying its chief
executive Lord Cairns, will succeed chairman Mr David Scholey when he
retires in 1995.
There will be no new chief executive: Lord Cairns, with the title of
executive chairman, will fill both roles. This is a departure from
recommended best practice for corporate boards which urges separation of the
roles.
Meanwhile, Warburg also said that its 90-year old co-founder and senior
president, Mr Henry Grunfeld, would no longer hold that position from next
year. Mr Grunfeld, who emigrated to Britain in 1934, founded the original
New Trading Company with the late Mr Sigmund Warburg.
The announcement came as Warburg revealed record profits of Pounds 297m for
the year to March 31, despite a 40 per cent rise in salary costs and a
slowdown in trading profits in the second half.
Speculation about a new chief executive had centred on Mr Nick Verey,
managing director of investment banking and Mr Derek Higgs, a managing
director at SG Warburg and Co. Under the new structure, Mr Verey, 51 and Mr
Higgs, 50, will be chairmen of SG Warburg Securities and SG Warburg and Co
respectively.
Mr Hugh Stevenson, chairman of Warburg's 75 per cent-owned fund management
arm, Mercury Asset Management, will form the third divisional chairman.
A spokesman for MAM, which has been a frequent, although quiet, participant
in corporate governance matters as a shareholder, said the group had no view
on whether companies are best run by separate chairmen and chief executives.
Meanwhile, MAM, reported a 33 per cent jump in pre-tax profits to Pounds
109.5m, despite a 30 per cent rise in operating costs following increases in
performance related pay and staffing.
MAM also said it had provisionally agreed to buy the 50 per cent of the
Geneva-based Bank SG Warburg Soditic AG it does not already own. It will pay
Pounds 48.3m cash, roughly twice the sum paid to SG Warburg for the first 50
per cent in 1990.
Mr Stevenson said the transaction would further MAM's ambitions in private
client fund management. MAM is trying to ease its dependence on the UK
institutional market and diversify into retail and international fund
management.
Lex, Page 26; Details, Page 29
