<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For reasons best known to themselves the people who run BBC2 have changed
the name of 'Business Matters' to The Business. The new series begins by
considering 'the rise and rise of Bill Gates', inventor of the DOS computer
system and head of Microsoft. At 38 he is said to possess a personal fortune
of seven billion dollars but, as David Lomax reports, is accused of unfair
business practices (7.20). That is followed by Wooldridge On Whisky, in
which the journalist tells the story of the famous drink. Did you know that
Humphrey Bogart on his death bed said 'I should never have switched from
Scotch to dry Martinis'? (8.00). The fashion for stretching successful
dramas to create comedy series, as with 'Outside Edge', continues in Moving
Story. Jack Rosenthal's original work was called 'The Chain' and told the
portmanteau tale of a sequence of house moves. In today's episode a new boy
joins the moving men (8.30 ITV). Subject of BBC2's series True Brits is the
'shoe string' style of the British embassies in the 15 states which used to
form the Soviet Union (9.30).
