<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Gas regulator feels pressure: Why Clare Spottiswoode has
fallen from favour among MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE and WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The appearance yesterday by Ms Clare Spottiswoode, Ofgas director general,
before a parliamentary select committee came amid a smear campaign directed
at her competence, the circumstances of her appointment and her personal
life.
Ms Spottiswoode adopted a conciliatory tone before the Commons environment
committee when she spoke about the financing of the Energy Savings Trust, a
key element of the government's environment policy.
It contrasted sharply with an earlier appearance during which she bluntly
rejected the idea of passing on the costs of energy efficincy projects to
gas consumers.
MPs say that earlier testimony infuriated Mr Robert Jones, the powerful
Conservative committee chairman who has championed the scheme. And it was
also at that appearance that she alleged that her predecessor, Sir James
McKinnon, had acted illegally in connection with implementing the programme,
a statement she yesterday withdrew 'unreservedly'.
But it is not clear whether her change in tone will end the smear campaign,
which culminated this week in allegations that Ms Spottiswoode had an affair
with Mr John Michell, a senior official at the Department of Trade and
Industry who was involved in her selection.
The DTI said it found no substance to back the allegations, and Ofgas
officials say they are in the dark as to who might be orchestrating the
campaign.
Many industry observers and politicians say her initial performance in front
of the committee prompted MPs and others to question her effectiveness. They
believe that other dissatisfied parties within the gas industry and
government simply joined the campaign as it gained momentum.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour spokesman on consumer affairs, noted that 'MPs
are an unforgiving bunch and have been reluctant to put her poor performance
down to inexperience. Her problem is that she has not made enough friends on
the way up.'
One executive at an independent gas marketer noted that 'enraged Tory MPs
don't like to be told what to do'.
Her suggestion that her predecessor had acted illegally clearly angered Sir
James. She is said to be deeply embarrassed by the incident, and the two are
no longer on speaking terms.
One gas industry executive says the present frosty relationship is similar
to that between Baroness Thatcher and Sir Edward Heath.
Changes made at Ofgas by Ms Spottiswoode may also have alienated some staff
members who were particularly close to Sir James.
Some DTI officials may also feel miffed that Ofgas is taking the lead role
in de-regulation, although Mr Tim Eggar, the energy minister, is known to
have expressed strong support for Ms Spottiswoode. Mr Michael Heseltine,
trade and industry secretary, is said by some officials to be 'wishing that
the whole thing would just go away'.
There has been speculation that some members of the government believe gas
liberalisation will prove to be such a politically explosive issue close to
the next election that the process should be slowed. One way to do this
would be to deflect criticism onto the regulator.
But the government could simply stall the process by not putting forward the
necessary legislation.
Independent gas marketers believe British Gas may also be whipping up press
scare stories about widespread price rises as a result of opening up the
domestic market. There are even suggestions that members of the British Gas
'old guard' may be fighting a rearguard action against the introduction of
competition.
Industry and Ofgas officials are concerned that the persistence of the smear
campaign could endanger the liberalisation process.
But Ms Spottiswoode appears determined to ride out the storm, although
officials worry that her propensity for plain speaking and clear aversion to
the present financing of the Energy Savings Trust could lead to additional
difficulties.
</TEXT>
